{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Views & Templating</h1>
    <p>
        The View layer is responsible for presenting data to the user. Rhapsody uses the powerful <a href="https://twig.symfony.com/" target="_blank">Twig</a>
        templating engine to keep your presentation logic separate from your PHP code. This makes your HTML cleaner, more secure, and easier to manage.
    </p>
    <p>All view files are located in the <code>views/</code> directory and use the <code>.twig</code> extension.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>The <code>@core</code> Namespace and Styling</h2>
    <p>
        When you use the <code>@core</code> namespace in your templates (e.g., <code>&#123;&#123;% extends "@core/layouts/main.twig" %&#125;&#125;</code>), 
        you inherit the framework's default design system.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/40 border-l-4 border-blue-500 dark:border-blue-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300">Framework Styling:</strong>
        <ul class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300 mt-2 space-y-1">
            <li><strong>Tailwind CSS v4.3.2</strong> – The default theme uses Tailwind for all styling.</li>
            <li><strong>Dark mode support</strong> – Built-in light/dark/system theme switching.</li>
            <li><strong>Responsive by default</strong> – Mobile-first design with Tailwind's utility classes.</li>
            <li><strong>Google Fonts</strong> – Montserrat font family is pre-loaded.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Adding Custom CSS to the Core Theme</h3>
    <p>
        If you want to keep the framework's default styling but add your own custom CSS, you should:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Copy the core <code>main.twig</code> to your theme:</strong>
            <pre><code class="language-bash">cp vendor/arout/rhapsody-core/resources/views/themes/default/layouts/main.twig views/themes/your-theme/layouts/main.twig</code></pre>
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Add your custom stylesheets in the <code>styles</code> block:</strong>
            <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;% block styles %&#125;
    &#123;# 1. Keep the core Tailwind styles (or replace them) #&#125;
    &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/css/app.css"&gt;
    
    &#123;# 2. Your custom styles #&#125;
    &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/css/custom.css"&gt;
    
    &#123;# 3. Keep the Google Fonts #&#125;
    &lt;link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com"&gt;
    &lt;link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin&gt;
    &lt;link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Montserrat:ital,wght@0,100..900;1,100..900&amp;display=swap" rel="stylesheet"&gt;
&#123;% endblock %&#125;</code></pre>
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Create your CSS files in <code>/public/css/</code>:</strong>
            <pre><code class="language-bash">public/css/app.css
public/css/custom.css</code></pre>
        </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="bg-yellow-50 dark:bg-yellow-950/40 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 dark:border-yellow-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300">💡 Tip:</strong>
        <p class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300 mt-1">
            If you're using a build tool (like Vite or Webpack), you can output your compiled CSS to 
            <code>/public/css/</code> and reference it with <code>&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/css/app.css</code>.
        </p>
    </div>

    <h3>Replacing the Core Theme Entirely</h3>
    <p>
        If you want to completely replace the framework's styling (e.g., use Bootstrap instead of Tailwind):
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>Create a <strong>new theme</strong> in <code>views/themes/your-theme/</code></li>
        <li>Create your own <code>layouts/main.twig</code> from scratch</li>
        <li>Set <code>APP_THEME=your-theme</code> in your <code>.env</code> file</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
        See the <a href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/docs/themes">Theme Customization</a> guide for more details – new themes must include certain core Twig blocks (e.g. <code>&#123;% block head %&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;% block content %&#125;</code>, etc.)
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Global Twig Variables</h2>
    <p>
        The framework automatically makes the following variables available in <strong>every</strong> Twig template:
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
                <tr class="bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700">
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Variable</th>
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Type</th>
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The full base URL of your application. Use this for all links.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; app_url &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The APP_URL from your <code>.env</code> file.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; app_env &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The current environment (<code>development</code>, <code>production</code>, etc.)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; app_theme &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The active theme name from <code>APP_THEME</code> in <code>.env</code>.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; auth.check &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">bool</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400"><code>true</code> if a user is logged in, <code>false</code> otherwise.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; auth.user &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">object|null</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The logged-in user object (with <code>name</code>, <code>email</code>, <code>user_id</code>, etc.) or <code>null</code> if not logged in.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; flash.success &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string|null</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Success flash message (displayed once, then cleared).</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; flash.error &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string|null</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Error flash message (displayed once, then cleared).</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td class="p-3"><code>&#123;&#123; schema_markup &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">string</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">JSON-LD structured data for SEO (rendered at the end of the page).</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/40 border-l-4 border-blue-500 dark:border-blue-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg mt-4">
        <strong class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300">💡 Additional Variables:</strong>
        <p class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300 mt-1">
            You can also access any data passed from your controller via the second argument to 
            <code>view()</code> or <code>react()</code>. These are merged into the template's context.
        </p>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Twig Functions</h2>
    <p>
        The framework provides several useful Twig functions that you can use in your templates:
    </p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
                <tr class="bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700">
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Function</th>
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Description</th>
                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Example</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>route()</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Generates a URL for a named route with optional parameters.</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 font-mono text-sm"><code>&#123;&#123; route('auth.redirect', {provider: 'facebook'}) &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>csrf_field()</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Outputs a hidden input field with a CSRF token.</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 font-mono text-sm"><code>&#123;&#123; csrf_field() &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>vite_assets()</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Loads Vite assets (dev server or production build).</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 font-mono text-sm"><code>&#123;&#123; vite_assets('resources/js/app.jsx') &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">
                    <td class="p-3"><code>react_component()</code></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Embeds a React component as an "island" in a Twig template.</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 font-mono text-sm"><code>&#123;&#123; react_component('UserStats', {userId: 1}) &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td class="p-3"><code>captcha_form</code> <small>(variable)</small></td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Raw HTML for a CAPTCHA form (rendered with <code>|raw</code> filter).</td>
                    <td class="p-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 font-mono text-sm"><code>&#123;&#123; captcha_form|raw &#125;&#125;</code></td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Using the <code>route()</code> Function</h3>
    <p>
        The <code>route()</code> function generates URLs based on named routes defined in your <code>routes/web.php</code> file.
        This is the preferred way to create links because it keeps your URLs maintainable:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;# Simple route without parameters #&#125;
&lt;a href="&#123;&#123; route('home') &#125;&#125;"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;

&#123;# Route with parameters #&#125;
&lt;a href="&#123;&#123; route('profile.show', {id: user.id}) &#125;&#125;"&gt;View Profile&lt;/a&gt;

&#123;# Route with query parameters #&#125;
&lt;a href="&#123;&#123; route('users.index', {page: 2, sort: 'name'}) &#125;&#125;"&gt;Page 2&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>

    <div class="bg-yellow-50 dark:bg-yellow-950/40 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 dark:border-yellow-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300">💡 Tip:</strong>
        <p class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300 mt-1">
            Named routes are defined in your <code>routes/web.php</code> file using the <code>->name()</code> method:
            <br>
            <code class="font-mono text-sm">$router->get('/profile/{id}', [ProfileController::class, 'show'])->name('profile.show');</code>
        </p>
    </div>

    <h3>Using the <code>captcha_form</code> Variable</h3>
    <p>
        If you have CAPTCHA functionality enabled, the <code>captcha_form</code> variable contains the raw HTML for the CAPTCHA widget.
        Use the <code>|raw</code> filter to render it:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&lt;form method="POST" action="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/submit"&gt;
    &#123;# Render the CAPTCHA widget #&#125;
    &#123;&#123; captcha_form|raw &#125;&#125;
    
    &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>

    <div class="bg-red-50 dark:bg-red-950/40 border-l-4 border-red-500 dark:border-red-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-red-800 dark:text-red-300">⚠️ Security Note:</strong>
        <p class="text-red-800 dark:text-red-300 mt-1">
            Always use the <code>|raw</code> filter when outputting <code>captcha_form</code>, as it contains HTML markup that would otherwise be escaped by Twig. 
            Only use <code>|raw</code> with trusted content – the framework ensures <code>captcha_form</code> is safe.
        </p>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Layouts and Inheritance</h2>
    <p>
        One of Twig's most powerful features is template inheritance. Instead of repeating your site's header and footer in every file, you can create
        a base layout and have other templates "extend" it.
    </p>
    <p>Our framework uses <code>views/layouts/main.twig</code> as the main site template. It contains all the common HTML, including the header, navigation, and footer.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">&lt;!-- views/layouts/main.twig --&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;header&gt;...&lt;/header&gt;
        
        &lt;main&gt;
            &#123;% block content %&#125;&#123;% endblock %&#125;
        &lt;/main&gt;

        &lt;footer&gt;...&lt;/footer&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>A specific page template then extends this layout and provides content only for the <code>content</code> block.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">&#123;# views/home/index.twig #&#125;
&#123;% extends "layouts/main.twig" %&#125;

&#123;% block content %&#125;
    &lt;h1&gt;Welcome to the Home Page!&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;This is the content for our home page.&lt;/p&gt;
&#123;% endblock %&#125;</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Displaying Data</h2>
    <p>You can print data passed from your controller using double curly braces: <code>&#123;&#123; ... &#125;&#125;</code>. Twig automatically escapes this output to prevent XSS attacks, making it secure by default.</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// In your controller
return $this->view('profile.twig', ['username' => 'Alice']);

&#123;# In profile.twig #&#125;
&lt;h1&gt;Welcome, &#123;&#123; username &#125;&#125;!&lt;/h1&gt;</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Working with Flash Messages</h2>

    <h3>Creating Flash Messages in Controllers</h3>
    <p>
        Flash messages are temporary messages that are stored in the session and displayed once, then automatically cleared.
        You can create them using the <code>->with()</code> method when returning a redirect response:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// In your controller
public function submitForm(Request $request): Response
{
    // ... process form data ...
    
    if ($success) {
        return redirect('/dashboard')->with('success', 'Your profile has been updated!');
    } else {
        return redirect('/profile')->with('error', 'There was a problem updating your profile.');
    }
}</code></pre>

    <p>
        The <code>redirect()</code> helper returns a <code>RedirectResponse</code> object, and <code>->with()</code> 
        accepts two arguments: the flash message <strong>type</strong> and the message <strong>content</strong>.
    </p>

    <h3>Displaying Flash Messages in Templates</h3>
    <p>
        Flash messages are automatically available in all Twig templates via the <code>flash</code> global variable.
        The main layout template already includes a section to display <code>success</code> and <code>error</code> messages.
    </p>

    <p>You can display them manually in any template like this:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;% if flash.success %&#125;
    &lt;div class="alert-success"&gt;&#123;&#123; flash.success &#125;&#125;&lt;/div&gt;
&#123;% endif %&#125;

&#123;% if flash.error %&#125;
    &lt;div class="alert-error"&gt;&#123;&#123; flash.error &#125;&#125;&lt;/div&gt;
&#123;% endif %&#125;</code></pre>

    <p>
        The main layout file <code>@core/layouts/main.twig</code> already includes this logic, so you don't need to add it to every template.
        However, you can add additional flash types (like <code>warning</code> or <code>info</code>) by creating them in your controller
        and displaying them in your templates accordingly.
    </p>

    <h3>Creating Custom Flash Messages</h3>
    <p>
        You're not limited to <code>success</code> and <code>error</code>. You can use any key you want:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// In your controller
return redirect('/dashboard')->with('warning', 'Your session is about to expire.');
return redirect('/dashboard')->with('info', 'A new update is available.');</code></pre>

    <p>
        And in your template:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&#123;% if flash.warning %&#125;
    &lt;div class="alert-warning"&gt;&#123;&#123; flash.warning &#125;&#125;&lt;/div&gt;
&#123;% endif %&#125;

&#123;% if flash.info %&#125;
    &lt;div class="alert-info"&gt;&#123;&#123; flash.info &#125;&#125;&lt;/div&gt;
&#123;% endif %&#125;</code></pre>

    <div class="bg-yellow-50 dark:bg-yellow-950/40 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 dark:border-yellow-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300">💡 Tip:</strong>
        <p class="text-yellow-800 dark:text-yellow-300 mt-1">
            Flash messages are <strong>one-time use</strong>. After they are displayed, they are automatically cleared from the session.
            This makes them perfect for showing feedback after form submissions, logins, or other actions.
        </p>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <div class="bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-950/40 border-l-4 border-green-500 dark:border-green-400 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
        <strong class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300">Need Help?</strong>
        <p class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300 mt-1">
            Check the <a href="&#123;&#123; base_url &#125;&#125;/docs/faq" class="text-green-800 dark:text-green-300 underline">FAQ</a> 
            or open an issue on GitHub.
        </p>
    </div>

{% endblock %}